{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/2018-06-02-design-patterns-1/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"John D Potts","author":"John Potts"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"1d817a9d-6ce5-5f42-a9c6-36b762aa78bd","html":"<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/9b3233c085e978e377feadb091b89783/0f98f/building-blocks.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 420px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 66.66666666666666%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"Building Blocks\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/9b3233c085e978e377feadb091b89783/65f94/building-blocks.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/9b3233c085e978e377feadb091b89783/d2682/building-blocks.jpg 105w,\n/static/9b3233c085e978e377feadb091b89783/60342/building-blocks.jpg 210w,\n/static/9b3233c085e978e377feadb091b89783/65f94/building-blocks.jpg 420w,\n/static/9b3233c085e978e377feadb091b89783/828fb/building-blocks.jpg 630w,\n/static/9b3233c085e978e377feadb091b89783/bba1f/building-blocks.jpg 840w,\n/static/9b3233c085e978e377feadb091b89783/0f98f/building-blocks.jpg 1920w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 420px) 100vw, 420px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>The Module Pattern is one of the most commonly used design patterns in Javascript. The module pattern exists to create privacy and separation in your code- keeping variables and functions out of the global scope.</p>\n<p>The module pattern presents as an <em>Immediately-Invoked Function Expression</em> (IIFE). All that an IIFE does is create a function which is called immediately. Here’s an example:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\">\n      <pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token keyword\">function</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n    <span class=\"token comment\">// Oh look, I'm hanging out inside a module</span>\n    <span class=\"token comment\">// How wonderful</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p> Or, with an ES6 arrow function,</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\">\n      <pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token operator\">=></span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n <span class=\"token comment\">// All of the mapping, reducing and filtering. ES6 FTW.</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>All of the variables and functions declared within the IIFE are kept out of the global scope.</p>\n<p>The module can also be namespaced in order to lay the groundwork for returning publicly accessible methods and properties:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\">\n      <pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\"><span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> myModule <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token operator\">=></span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n <span class=\"token keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n   <span class=\"token function-variable function\">publicMethod</span><span class=\"token operator\">:</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">function</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n     console<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">log</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'hello.'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n     <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n   <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\nmyModule<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">publicMethod</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// hello.</span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>A close relative to the Module Pattern is something called the Revealing Module Pattern. This is a module that returns certain properties or methods in an easy-to-read syntax, thus revealing part of itself for public use:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\">\n      <pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\"><span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> myModule <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token operator\">=></span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n\n <span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> <span class=\"token function-variable function\">privateMethod</span> <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">function</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n   console<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">log</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token template-string\"><span class=\"token template-punctuation string\">`</span><span class=\"token string\">shhhh, it's a secret</span><span class=\"token template-punctuation string\">`</span></span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n   <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n <span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> privateVariable <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token string\">'foo'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n <span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> <span class=\"token function-variable function\">publicMethod</span> <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">function</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n   console<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">log</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'hello'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n <span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> publicVariable <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token string\">'bar'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n <span class=\"token keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n   publicMethod<span class=\"token operator\">:</span> publicMethod<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n   publicVariable<span class=\"token operator\">:</span> publicVariable\n <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>This makes only the defined methods and variables accessible outside the module, and is easy to read since the return object is generally put at the bottom of the module.</p>","excerpt":"The Module Pattern is one of the most commonly used design patterns in Javascript. The module pattern exists to create privacy and…","fields":{"slug":"/2018-06-02-design-patterns-1/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Design Patterns in JS: The Module Pattern","date":"June 02, 2018","recommended":null,"featuredImage":{"childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"src":"/static/9b3233c085e978e377feadb091b89783/a7715/building-blocks.jpg"}}}}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/2018-06-02-design-patterns-1/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/2018-05-26-self-teaching/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Should You Attend a Developer Bootcamp?"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/2018-06-09-debugging-1/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Front End Debugging: Key Steps"}}}},"staticQueryHashes":["2913751889"]}